In this question, we can use a TreeSet which offers functinos like floor and ceiling. 
**floor()** returns the greatest element in this set less than or equal to the given element, or null if there is no such element. 
**ceiling()** returns the least element in this set greater than or equal to the given element, or null if there is no such element. 

At all times, the TreeSet will represent **a  window of k numbers**. When the index goes beyond k, we keep on removing index-k th number form the TreeSet.

```
public boolean containsNearbyAlmostDuplicate(int[] nums, int k, int t) {
	if(nums.length == 0) return false;
	TreeSet<Long> window = new TreeSet<>();
	for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++) {
		long num = nums[i];
		Long floor = window.floor(num+t);
		Long ceiling = window.ceiling(num-t);
		if(floor != null && floor >= num) return true;
		if(ceiling !=null && ceiling <= num) return true;
		window.add(num);
		if(i >= k) window.remove((long)nums[i-k]);
	}
	return false;
}
```

