Coming up with this solution, think of it like a number line.
If you want the difference of x and y to be 0 then you want x = y (on top of each other).
As you raise the allowed difference, think of the allowed range increasing in both positive and negative direction equally.
E.g. allowed distance is 'k' then x can be in range [y - k, y +k] and y can be in range [x - k, x +k].

And TreeSet is perfect for testing range.contains.

You could read about https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics).

```
  public boolean containsNearbyAlmostDuplicate(int[] nums, int k, int t) {
    if (t < 0) {
      return false;
    }

    // sliding window
	// Need ugly Long to handle int overflows.
    TreeSet<Long> set = new TreeSet<>();

    for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
      // abs difference
      // |nums[i] - nums[j]| <= t

      // if nums[j] <= nums[i] then:
      // nums[i] - t <= nums[j]

      // if nums[j] >= nums[i] then:
      // nums[j] <= t + nums[i]

      // which is:
      // nums[i] - t <= nums[j] <= t + nums[i]

      // basically, is there anything in the range [num - t, num + t]?

      if (!set.subSet((long) nums[i] - t, true, (long) nums[i] + t, true).isEmpty()) {
        return true;
      }

      set.add((long) nums[i]);
      if (set.size() > k) {
        set.remove((long) nums[i - k]);
      }
    }
    return false;
  }
