solutions.content:
1. Initialize a Tree Set.  It can be imagined as a constantly updating binary search tree.  This means we can find the max and min values currently in the tree in an average O(log n) time. Where n is the amount of elements in the tree.
2. We then run through the list of numbers.  For each number, n, we check the tree for the current floor and cieling of n.  The floor is the largest number currently in the tree that is less then n.  The cieling is the smallest.
3. From here, we check to see if the cieling minus our current n is within the acceptable range (val diff).  If there is, we can stop looping and just return true. Same thing with the current n minus the floor.
4. We then add n to the tree set.  If the tree is now larger than the excepted indDifference we remove the first element that was added to the current tree.  This can be done by subtracting the current index, i, from the indDiff value.  This is because indDiff is the max number of elements allowed in the tree. 
5. If we complete the loop through the list there was no valid cases, so we can return false.

*Note that we convert all the ints to longs because if we have MAX Value or MIN Value or any combination where we would add or subtract and go out of bounds, long can handle those larger numbers.


```
public boolean containsNearbyAlmostDuplicate(int[] nums, int indDiff, int valDiff) {
		TreeSet<Long> set = new TreeSet<Long>();
		for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
			Long floor = set.floor((long) nums[i]); // Largest Number less then the num.
			Long cieling = set.ceiling((long) nums[i]); // Smallest Number greater than num.

		    if (floor != null && (long) nums[i] - floor <= valDiff) return true;
			if (cieling != null && cieling - (long) nums[i] <= valDiff) return true;

			set.add((long)nums[i]);
			if(set.size()>indDiff) set.remove((long)nums[i-indDiff]);
		}
		return false;
	}

