solutions.content:
Clarify:
return true if (nums[i] - nums[j]) <= t && j - i <= k

Method1: Sliding Window

Window size: k + 1

if(max - min <= t) return ture;

TC: O(k + (n-k)*k)
SC: O(k)

Method2: Using Balanced Binary Search Tree to reduce time to find cloest number.

1. Build a size (k + 1) bbs tree
2. Traverse the rest (n - k - 1) elements
    Step1: remove the last element ==> remove(nums[i - k])
    Step2: find the cloest number to the new element ==> findCloestInTree(nums[i])
            if foundElement - nums[i] <= t ==> return true
    Step3: add new element into tree ==> add(nums[i])
```
class Solution {
    public boolean containsNearbyAlmostDuplicate(int[] nums, int k, int t) {
        TreeSet<Integer> bbsTree = new TreeSet<>();
        int output = 2147483647 - (-1);
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if(i > k) {
                bbsTree.remove(nums[i - k - 1]);
            }
            Integer ceil = bbsTree.ceiling(nums[i]);
            if(ceil != null && ceil <= t + nums[i]) {
                return true;
            }
            Integer floor = bbsTree.floor(nums[i]);
            if(floor != null && nums[i] <= t + floor) {
                return true;
            }
            bbsTree.add(nums[i]);
        }
        return false;
    }
}
```
TC: O(k + (n - k)logk)
SC: O(k)

Method3: Using Buckets to save the range numbers. Each bucket save range t numbers.
Each time, we find get save target into one bucket:
    1. if bucket is filled, return true;   
    2. if last bucket or next bucket is filled and difference between number in those bucket with current element is <= k, return true
    3. implement current bucket
Implementation: We use a map<Double, Integer> to save target Number and index
TC: O(n))
SC: O(buket_size) Worst Case: O(maximum number - minimum number)

