solutions.content:
Approach:
1. We walk through the numbers left to right linearly keeping a sliding window of width `k`
2. We maintain the numbers that lie within this sliding window inside of "buckets". Each bucket has a `bucket-id` which is continguous and has width `t + 1`. This ensures that if two numbers `x` and `y` are such that they get placed in the same bucket i.e. have same `bucket-id`, then `|x - y| <= t`
3. So, as we slide our window of width `k` across the array, we'd have exactly `k` buckets maintained (Otherwise, by the pigeonhole principle, we'd have atleast two numbers that lie in the same bucket and we've found a solution)
4. Additionally, when adding a new element in our window, we also have to check neighbouring buckets to see if they have a number that lies within `t` distance of the newcomer.


```
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsNearbyAlmostDuplicate(vector<int>& nums, int k, int t) {
        // Impossible to have two distinct indices that are k apart
        if(size(nums) < 2 || k < 1)
            return false;

        // This is because we compute t+1 and given the bounds on t, that can overflow for int
        // So, we need a large type
        using val_t_ = long;

        // id-of-bucket -> element
        // As we'll see later we'd need to ever keep only a single element with a given bucket-id
        // even though the bucket_size is t + 1.
        unordered_map<val_t_, val_t_> bucket;

        //  ...   {-1 : -bucket_size, ...    , -2, -1},
        //        { 0 : 0, 1, 2, ..., bucket_size - 1},
        //        { 1 : bucket_size, bucket_size + 1, ..., 2*bucket_size - 1}, ...
        auto bucket_id = [](val_t_ num, val_t_ bucket_size) {
            if(num < 0)
                return ((num + 1) / bucket_size) - 1;  // ensure uniform bucket_size
            return num / bucket_size;
        };

        // +1 because t can be zero
        // The fact that any two elements in buckets of size t+1
        // are at most t apart (inclusive) still holds
        // In fact t+1 is the largest bucket size for which this holds.
        auto bucket_size = static_cast<val_t_>(t) + 1;

        for(int i = 0; i < size(nums); i++) {
            auto const &num = nums[i];
            auto id = bucket_id(num, bucket_size);

            // Already have something in this bucket, newcomer 'num' is guaranteed to be at most "t" away from this old resident
            if(bucket.count(id))
                return true;

            // elements in immediate neighbouring buckets can also be within "t" of the newcomer
            // No other buckets would have any elements at most "t" closer.
            // This would not have been guaranteed if bucket_size were smaller than t+1
            for(auto neighbour : {id - 1, id + 1})
                if(auto it = bucket.find(neighbour); it != bucket.end() && abs(it->second - num) <= t)
                    return true;

            // Add current element to bucket (and the sliding window)
            bucket[id] = num;

            // If we go through k numbers without exiting early above, that means all of those
            // have landed in different buckets. So bucket size must be same as our sliding window size.
            // Here we remove the leftmost element from the bucket (and from the sliding window)
            // to keep the invariant that the indices are at most k apart.
            if(bucket.size() > k)
                bucket.erase(bucket_id(nums[i - k], bucket_size));
        }

        return false;
    }
};
```

