# Intuition
It is already mentioned that this problem must be solved using Binary Search.

# Approach
We will be taking 2 pointers (let say st and en) initially pointed at the ends of the array. 

Now consider the middle element between 2 pointers (let say m).

if(nums[m] == target): 
Yes we found the element at index m so return it.

if(target < nums[m]):
As vector is in ascending order, nums[m]<=nums[m+1]<=nums[m+2]<=....nums[en].
So target will be less than all the elements in the index range [m,en]. Target can be found in the index range [st,m-1]. 

**Update en = m-1.**(Searching in left half of array).

if(target>nums[m]):
As vector is in ascending order, nums[st]>=nums[st+1]>=nums[st+2]>=....nums[m].
So target will be greater than all the elements in the index range [st,m]. Target can be found in the index range [m+1,en].

**Update st = m+1.**(Seaching in right half of array).

**If not found after traversing whole array return -1 at the end.**

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(logN)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int st = 0;
        int en = nums.size()-1;
        while(st<=en){
            int m = (en+st)/2;
            if(nums[m] == target){
                return m;
            }else if(nums[m]>target){
                en = m-1;
            }else{
                st = m+1;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

